1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:11,490
Chapter 4 How to Think Big Recently, I chatted with a recruitment specialist for one of the nation's largest industrial organizations.

2
00:00:11,759 --> 00:00:20,290
Four months each year, she visits college campuses to recruit graduating seniors for her company's junior executive training program.

3
00:00:20,480 --> 00:00:27,649
The tenor of her remarks indicated that she was discouraged about the attitudes of many people she talked with.

4
00:00:28,160 --> 00:00:34,770
Most days, I interview between eight and twelve college seniors, all in the upper third of their class,

5
00:00:34,880 --> 00:00:38,049
all at least mildly interested in coming with us.

6
00:00:38,240 --> 00:00:44,290
One of the main things we want to determine in the screening interview is the individual's motivation.

7
00:00:44,480 --> 00:00:48,689
We want to find out if he or she is the kind of person who can,

8
00:00:48,720 --> 00:00:54,049
in a few years, direct major projects, manage a branch office or plant,

9
00:00:54,080 --> 00:00:58,610
or in some other way make a really substantial contribution to the company.

10
00:00:59,040 --> 00:01:04,850
I must say I'm not too pleased with the personal objectives of most of those I talk with.

11
00:01:05,200 --> 00:01:07,729
You'd be surprised," she went on.

12
00:01:07,920 --> 00:01:14,690
How many 22-year-olds are more interested in our retirement plan than in anything else we have to offer?

13
00:01:14,880 --> 00:01:18,850
A second favorite question is, will I move around a lot?

14
00:01:19,119 --> 00:01:24,290
Most of them seem to define the word success as synonymous with security.

15
00:01:24,479 --> 00:01:28,130
Can we risk turning our company over to people like that?

16
00:01:28,640 --> 00:01:34,690
The thing I can't understand is why should young people these days be so ultra-conservative,

17
00:01:34,880 --> 00:01:37,250
so narrow in their view of the future?

18
00:01:37,600 --> 00:01:41,089
Every day there are more signs of expanding opportunity.

19
00:01:41,280 --> 00:01:46,449
This country is making record progress in scientific and industrial development.

20
00:01:46,640 --> 00:01:49,169
Our population is gaining rapidly.

21
00:01:49,280 --> 00:01:53,649
If there ever was a time to be bullish about America, it's now.

22
00:01:54,560 --> 00:02:03,009
The tendency for so many people to think small means there is less competition than you think for a very rewarding career.

23
00:02:03,440 --> 00:02:11,169
Where success is concerned, people are not measured in inches or pounds or college degrees or family background.

24
00:02:11,359 --> 00:02:14,130
They are measured by the size of their thinking.

25
00:02:14,479 --> 00:02:18,609
How big we think determines the size of our accomplishments.

26
00:02:18,880 --> 00:02:22,210
Now, let's see how we can enlarge our thinking.

